{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01BnFxNoENmQBYGtfWeALcQs","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t---\n2\ttitle: TypeScript Public Interface\n3\tdate: 2026-04-24\n4\ttarget_release: 0.6.0\n5\tdesc: Public TypeScript surface for 0.6.0\n6\tblast_radius: src/ts/; design/bindings.md; design/errors.md; design/lifecycle.md; design/engine.md\n7\tstatus: locked\n8\t---\n9\t\n10\t# TypeScript Interface\n11\t\n12\tThis file owns TypeScript-visible symbol spelling and export shape. Cross-\n13\tbinding parity remains owned by `design/bindings.md`.\n14\t\n15\t## Runtime surface\n16\t\n17\tThe canonical runtime verbs available to TypeScript callers are:\n18\t\n19\t- `Engine.open(...)`\n20\t- `engine.write(...)`\n21\t- `engine.search(...)`\n22\t- `engine.close()`\n23\t- `admin.configure(...)`\n24\t\n25\tAll runtime operations are Promise-returning on the TS surface.\n26\t\n27\t`Engine.open(...)` returns the engine handle plus the structured open report\n28\towned by `design/engine.md`.\n29\t\n30\t> **0.6.0 caveat (2026-05-17, Phase 12-TX).** The napi-rs binding currently\n31\t> returns the engine handle only; the structured open report is dropped.\n32\t> Native Rust `Engine::open` returns `OpenedEngine { engine, report:\n33\t> OpenReport }` and the report is populated, but binding-side surfacing\n34\t> defers to 0.6.1 (slice 12-TX-OPENREPORT). Clients that need\n35\t> migration-version-reached / embedder-identity-confirmed / open-stage\n36\t> data wait for 0.6.1.\n37\t\n38\t`Engine.open(path, options?)` accepts an options object with an `engineConfig`\n39\tmember carrying the engine-owned knobs from `design/engine.md` in camelCase:\n40\t\n41\t- `embedderPoolSize`\n42\t- `schedulerRuntimeThreads`\n43\t- `provenanceRowCap`\n44\t- `embedderCallTimeoutMs`\n45\t- `slowThresholdMs`\n46\t\n47\tIf TypeScript exposes ThreadsafeFunction handoff-pool sizing, that option is a\n48\tTS binding-runtime option beside `engineConfig`, not a canonical engine config\n49\tfield and not a Python parity obligation.\n50\t\n51\t## Engine-attached instrumentation / control\n52\t\n53\tThese are public instance methods, not extra top-level SDK verbs:\n54\t\n55\t- `engine.drain(timeoutMs)`\n56\t- `engine.counters()`\n57\t- `engine.setProfiling(enabled)`\n58\t- `engine.setSlowThresholdMs(value)`\n59\t\n60\tSubscriber attachment is provided by:\n61\t\n62\t- `engine.attachSubscriber(callback, { heartbeatIntervalMs? })`\n63\t\n64\t`callback` receives the stable `fathomdb` payload described in\n65\t`design/bindings.md`.\n66\t\n67\t## Caller-visible data shapes\n68\t\n69\t- `WriteReceipt.cursor`\n70\t- `SearchResult.projectionCursor`\n71\t- `SearchResult.softFallback.branch`\n72\t\n73\t`softFallback.branch` uses the typed values owned by `design/retrieval.md`.\n74\t\n75\t## Errors\n76\t\n77\tTypeScript exposes one concrete leaf class per canonical row in\n78\t`design/errors.md`.\n79\t\n80\tLeaf-class examples:\n81\t\n82\t- `DatabaseLockedError`\n83\t- `CorruptionError`\n84\t- `MigrationError`\n85\t- `IncompatibleSchemaVersionError`\n86\t- `EmbedderIdentityMismatchError`\n87\t- `EmbedderDimensionMismatchError`\n88\t- `SchemaValidationError`\n89\t- `OverloadedError`\n90\t- `ClosingError`\n91\t\n92\tTypeScript exports one catch-all base class, `FathomDbError`, and every\n93\tconcrete leaf class in the `design/errors.md` matrix extends it. Open-time and\n94\truntime leaf classes remain distinct, but callers can catch `FathomDbError`\n95\tfor both.\n96\t\n97\t## Non-presence\n98\t\n99\tTypeScript does not expose recovery verbs or doctor-only flags. In particular,\n100\tthere is no SDK equivalent of `recover`, `checkIntegrity`, `quick`, `full`, or\n101\t`roundTrip`. See `design/recovery.md`.\n102\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"c409cac9-fa4a-4d9f-9db5-55aae00050c6","uuid":"0309b3df-6fb0-4112-bcbe-9c6cb2ec0104","timestamp":"2026-05-17T21:02:29.385Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/tmp/fdb-12-DX-external-user-docs-20260517T210205Z/dev/interfaces/typescript.md","content":"---\ntitle: TypeScript Public Interface\ndate: 2026-04-24\ntarget_release: 0.6.0\ndesc: Public TypeScript surface for 0.6.0\nblast_radius: src/ts/; design/bindings.md; design/errors.md; design/lifecycle.md; design/engine.md\nstatus: locked\n---\n\n# TypeScript Interface\n\nThis file owns TypeScript-visible symbol spelling and export shape. Cross-\nbinding parity remains owned by `design/bindings.md`.\n\n## Runtime surface\n\nThe canonical runtime verbs available to TypeScript callers are:\n\n- `Engine.open(...)`\n- `engine.write(...)`\n- `engine.search(...)`\n- `engine.close()`\n- `admin.configure(...)`\n\nAll runtime operations are Promise-returning on the TS surface.\n\n`Engine.open(...)` returns the engine handle plus the structured open report\nowned by `design/engine.md`.\n\n> **0.6.0 caveat (2026-05-17, Phase 12-TX).** The napi-rs binding currently\n> returns the engine handle only; the structured open report is dropped.\n> Native Rust `Engine::open` returns `OpenedEngine { engine, report:\n> OpenReport }` and the report is populated, but binding-side surfacing\n> defers to 0.6.1 (slice 12-TX-OPENREPORT). Clients that need\n> migration-version-reached / embedder-identity-confirmed / open-stage\n> data wait for 0.6.1.\n\n`Engine.open(path, options?)` accepts an options object with an `engineConfig`\nmember carrying the engine-owned knobs from `design/engine.md` in camelCase:\n\n- `embedderPoolSize`\n- `schedulerRuntimeThreads`\n- `provenanceRowCap`\n- `embedderCallTimeoutMs`\n- `slowThresholdMs`\n\nIf TypeScript exposes ThreadsafeFunction handoff-pool sizing, that option is a\nTS binding-runtime option beside `engineConfig`, not a canonical engine config\nfield and not a Python parity obligation.\n\n## Engine-attached instrumentation / control\n\nThese are public instance methods, not extra top-level SDK verbs:\n\n- `engine.drain(timeoutMs)`\n- `engine.counters()`\n- `engine.setProfiling(enabled)`\n- `engine.setSlowThresholdMs(value)`\n\nSubscriber attachment is provided by:\n\n- `engine.attachSubscriber(callback, { heartbeatIntervalMs? })`\n\n`callback` receives the stable `fathomdb` payload described in\n`design/bindings.md`.\n\n## Caller-visible data shapes\n\n- `WriteReceipt.cursor`\n- `SearchResult.projectionCursor`\n- `SearchResult.softFallback.branch`\n\n`softFallback.branch` uses the typed values owned by `design/retrieval.md`.\n\n## Errors\n\nTypeScript exposes one concrete leaf class per canonical row in\n`design/errors.md`.\n\nLeaf-class examples:\n\n- `DatabaseLockedError`\n- `CorruptionError`\n- `MigrationError`\n- `IncompatibleSchemaVersionError`\n- `EmbedderIdentityMismatchError`\n- `EmbedderDimensionMismatchError`\n- `SchemaValidationError`\n- `OverloadedError`\n- `ClosingError`\n\nTypeScript exports one catch-all base class, `FathomDbError`, and every\nconcrete leaf class in the `design/errors.md` matrix extends it. Open-time and\nruntime leaf classes remain distinct, but callers can catch `FathomDbError`\nfor both.\n\n## Non-presence\n\nTypeScript does not expose recovery verbs or doctor-only flags. In particular,\nthere is no SDK equivalent of `recover`, `checkIntegrity`, `quick`, `full`, or\n`roundTrip`. See `design/recovery.md`.\n","numLines":102,"startLine":1,"totalLines":102}}}
